            'Here’s what’s currently rumored for Apple’s 2026 MacBook lineup — based on leaks, analyst reports, and supply chain intel:\n\n---\n\n### 🍏 **New Low-Cost MacBook (2026)**\nApple is reportedly developing a budget-friendly MacBook aimed at students and casual users, priced under $1,000.  \n- **Chip**: Likely uses an iPhone-class A18 Pro or similar (not M-series) to cut costs.  \n- **Display**: Slightly smaller than the current 13.6-inch MacBook Air.  \n- **Launch window**: First half of 2026.  \n- **Purpose**: Compete with Chromebooks and entry-level Windows laptops [1].\n\n---\n\n### 💻 **M5 MacBook Air (13" & 15") – Early 2026**\nExpected as a straightforward chip upgrade.  \n- **Chip**: M5 (same as base 14" MacBook Pro).  \n- **Design**: No major changes — same body, ports, and keyboard.  \n- **Performance**: Better CPU/GPU, improved efficiency, same battery life.  \n- **Ideal for**: Users upgrading from M1 or Intel Airs [1].\n\n---\n\n### 🚀 **M5 Pro & M5 Max MacBook Pro (14" & 16") – Early 2026**\nAlready refreshed in March 2026 with M5 Pro and M5 Max chips.  \n- **No design changes** — same chassis, ports, and mini-LED displays.  \n- **Performance**:  \n  - M5 Pro: Up to 18-core CPU, 20-core GPU.  \n  - M5 Max: Up to 18-core CPU, 40-core GPU.  \n- **Memory**: Starts at 24GB RAM (Pro), 36GB (Max); max 64GB (Pro), 128GB (Max).  \n- **SSD**: Up to 8TB, with faster read/write speeds (up to 17.8 GB/s) [2].\n\n---\n\n### 🌟 **MacBook Ultra (Redesigned Pro) – Late 2026 or Early 2027**\nThis is the big one — a rumored *new tier* above the Pro, possibly called “MacBook Ultra.”  \n- **Display**: OLED (possibly with touch support) — first Mac with touchscreen [3].  \n- **Chip**: M6 Pro or M6 Max (built on 2nm process).  \n- **Design**: Thinner body, hole-punch camera (no notch), Dynamic Island-style UI.  \n- **Connectivity**: Built-in cellular (5G) rumored [4].  \n- **Timing**: May slip to early 2027 due to global memory chip shortages [13].  \n\n> *Note: Some reports suggest this model won’t replace the MacBook Pro but sit above it as a premium “Ultra” tier — similar to Apple Watch Ultra [11].*\n\n---\n\n### 📅 **What to Buy Now vs. Wait For**\n| If You Need... | Buy Now? | Wait For? |\n|----------------|----------|-----------|\n| Basic tasks, budget | ✅ Low-cost MacBook (if available) or M5 Air | — |\n| Pro performance | ✅ M5 Pro/Max MacBook Pro (refreshed March 2026) | MacBook Ultra (if OLED/touch is critical) |\n| Future-proof / flagship | — | MacBook Ultra (late 2026 or 2027) |\n\n---\n\n### 🔍 **Rumor Confidence Level**\n- **High**: M5 Air & Pro refreshes — consistent reporting, fits Apple’s cadence [1].  \n- **Medium**: Low-cost MacBook — multiple sources, but new category = risk of delay.  \n- **Medium**: MacBook Ultra — many details rumored, but 2027 is still possible [13].  \n- **Low**: Cellular Mac — mentioned, but not widely detailed [1].\n\n---\n\n### 🧩 **Bonus: What Else Is Coming?**\n- **Mac Studio**: Expected with M5 Max/Ultra chips — possibly delayed to October 2026 [7].  \n- **Foldable MacBook?** Rumored for much later — 18.8-inch all-display concept [2].  \n\n---\n\n**Bottom line**: If you need a Mac *now*, the M5 Pro/Max MacBook Pro (refreshed March 2026) is your best bet. If you’re after OLED, touch, or a true redesign, hold out for the “MacBook Ultra” — but be ready for a possible 2027 launch [13]. \n\n::search[MacBook Ultra 2026]{type=images}  \n::search[MacBook Pro M5 Max 2026]{type=web}',
